    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1979-07-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1979-07-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="282"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d282">
                <head>282. Memorandum for the Record<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d282fn1"
                        >Source: Central Intelligence Agency, Office of the Director of Central
                        Intelligence, Job 81B00112R: Subject Files, Box 16, Folder 36: (<gloss
                            target="#t_SCC_1">SCC</gloss>) Nicaragua. Secret; Sensitive. Drafted on
                        July 16. [<hi rend="italic">name not declassified</hi>] sent a copy of the
                        memorandum to <persName corresp="#p_TS_1">Turner</persName> under a July 16
                        covering memorandum, indicating that [<hi rend="italic">name not
                            declassified</hi>] had drafted the memorandum. For another account of
                        the meeting see <ref target="#d283">Document 283</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <idno type="document-identifier">NFAC–3713–79</idno>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1979-07-16">July 16, 1979</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_SCC_1">SCC</gloss> Meeting on Nicaragua, 16 July 1979,
                        White House Situation Room</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CW_1">Warren Christopher</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_VVPP_1">Viron Vaky</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_BJ_3"
                            >John Bushnell</persName>, State Department; <persName corresp="#p_BZ_1"
                            >Zbigniew Brzezinski</persName>, White House; <persName
                            corresp="#p_CFC_1">Frank Carlucci</persName>, [<hi rend="italic">name
                            not declassified</hi>] <gloss target="#t_CIA_1">CIA</gloss>; <persName
                            corresp="#p_JDC_2">David Jones</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_PJ_2"
                            >John Pustay</persName>, <gloss target="#t_JCS_1">JCS</gloss>; <persName
                            corresp="#p_PR_1">Robert Pastor</persName>, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1"
                            >NSC</gloss>; <persName corresp="#p_BH_4">Harold Brown</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_SG_1">Gordon Schuller</persName>, Defense
                        Department; John White, <gloss target="#t_OMB_1">OMB</gloss>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>1. Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_VVPP_1">Vaky</persName> said Somoza has
                    agreed to resign and leave Nicaragua before dawn, 17 July. He wants to name
                        <persName corresp="#p_SH_1">Heberto Sanchez</persName>—a very corrupt
                    retired Minister of Defense—to be new Guard commander. The provisional junta
                    rejected this outright. Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_PL_1"
                        >Pezzullo</persName> will tell Somoza today that the US prefers Col.
                        <persName corresp="#p_MIO_1">Mojica</persName>. If Somoza insists on
                        <persName corresp="#p_SH_1">Sanchez</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_PL_1"
                        >Pezzullo</persName> will express doubt that the junta will retain <persName
                        corresp="#p_SH_1">Sanchez</persName>, but that it is Somoza’s decision.
                    Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_BWG_1">Bowdler</persName> will tell the junta
                    that this is Somoza’s idea and it can be rectified once Somoza is gone.</p>
                <p>2. <persName corresp="#p_VVPP_1">Vaky</persName> said it appears that efforts to
                    get Andean foreign ministers to Managua to observe and perhaps pacify the
                    transition appear likely to fail. The Andeans are confused and unable to act
                    quickly.</p>
                <p>3. There was considerable discussion on relief and humanitarian assistance, the
                    modalities in Nicaragua, and the US contribution. General <persName
                        corresp="#p_JDC_2">Jones</persName> urged involving the Latin American
                    militaries through <persName corresp="#p_THO_1">Torrijos</persName> in a joint
                    effort with the Nicaraguan military to implement longer term reconstruction. US
                    concern that early relief flights be by chartered civilian aircraft—and not
                    military airlift—will initially hold down the volume of aid.</p>
                <p>4. Recognition of the new government was considered to be natural, but the
                    recognition statement will make reference to the provisional government’s
                    pledges. A statement may be issued tonight before Somoza’s departure, to avoid a
                    beating in the press.<note n="2" xml:id="d282fn2">See <ref target="#d283fn5"
                            >footnote 5, Document 283</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0746" n="695" xml:id="pg_695"/>
                <p>5. Following the meeting <gloss target="#t_DDCI_1">DDCI</gloss>
                    <persName corresp="#p_CFC_1">Carlucci</persName>, [<hi rend="italic">name not
                        declassified</hi>], <persName corresp="#p_PR_1">Robert Pastor</persName>,
                    and <persName corresp="#p_VVPP_1">Vaky</persName> briefly discussed the possible
                    role of covert action.</p>
            </div>
